# Workflow

The development cycle, described harness-neutrally. Each phase names what enters it, what it produces, and when to use it. Tools differ per harness; the phases do not.

## The cycle

`brainstorm → plan → execute → review`, with `quick` as the Tier 0–1 shortcut and `debug` as the root-cause entry point. The tier (`risk-tiers.md`) decides how much of the cycle a change runs through: Tier 0 commits directly when there is no behavior change (the branching rules in `commits.md` still apply) and otherwise takes the quick path, Tier 1 takes the quick path with a test, Tier 2 runs plan → execute → review, and Tier 3 adds an upfront brainstorm/design (and second-opinion review where configured).

## Brainstorm

Turns an idea into an approved design. Enters: a request or problem. Produces: a written design/spec the implementer can follow, plus explicit approval. Use before any non-trivial new behavior — do not start building until the design is agreed. Prefer a few clarifying questions over guessing the intent. Read the product frame (`PRODUCT.md`) and the decision records (`docs/process/adr/`) relevant to the area first — both are constraints, not open questions: a design that serves no stated goal or violates a non-goal says so and changes the frame in the same effort (or does not proceed); a design that overturns an endorsed decision names the supersession (mandatory rule 4). If the frame is still `not-onboarded`, the start-here onboarding dialogue fills it before product-shaped work. Brainstorm also decomposes the work's acceptance into concrete, testable criteria — including the negative, edge, authorization, and invalidation/cleanup cases the Definition of Ready names (R2, `definition-of-ready-and-done.md`); that readiness bar is binding, met before work starts or carried as a documented, justified deviation on the issue. For Tier 3 work, the design also answers the threat question — *what could an attacker do with this change?* (assets touched, new inputs, trust boundaries crossed) — so the review (`review-checklist.md`, Security) checks an answer instead of discovering the question.

## Plan

Turns an approved design into a zero-context task breakdown. Enters: the design/spec. Produces: a plan file (`journal-state-plans.md`) of bite-sized, independently testable tasks with exact files, code, and test commands. Assume the implementer knows the toolchain but not this codebase. Use for every Tier 2+ change. The plan names the decision records it read and any new or superseded record the change entails — or states that none apply — and the product goal (`PRODUCT.md`) the change serves, or that it is product-neutral (`journal-state-plans.md`, Plans).

## Execute

Implements the plan task by task. Enters: the plan. Produces: committed, tested code — one atomic commit per task (`commits.md`), following test-driven development (write the failing test, watch it fail, implement, watch it pass, commit). Re-read the kernel (`kernel.md`) and the plan at phase entry — a long build compacts, and the rules bind every task, not the first alone (`kernel.md`, "Keeping the kernel loaded" in `start-here.md`). Use as the build phase; keep tasks isolated so each is independently reviewable. A significant, hard-to-reverse decision discovered mid-build stops the task: record it as a decision record first, then write the code that assumes it (mandatory rule 4). Execute runs in the warm production context — the same context that planned the work (`verification-independence.md`).{% if modules.telemetry %} When grading acceptance criteria at checkpoints, append one `GRADE` line per criterion per round to the journal (`docs/process/modules/telemetry.md`).{% endif %}

## Review

The gate before merge to the main branch. Enters: the branch diff plus the plan/spec. Produces: a pass/fail judgment on functional completeness, correctness, and adherence to these rules. Re-read the kernel (`kernel.md`) and `mandatory-rules.md` at entry — the review judges the change against them, and a long session may have compacted them out. The required depth *and independence* scale with the tier (`risk-tiers.md`, `verification-independence.md`): a fresh process reviews a read-only bundle rather than the producing context, and the implementing agent does not self-certify. What a review actually checks — completeness, correctness, security, design, decisions, product frame, tests — is `review-checklist.md`. Use before every merge that the tier gates; fixes loop back through execute + review until clean. Review is the binding gate for the **Definition of Done** (`definition-of-ready-and-done.md`): it does not pass unless each applicable DoD item — including that the **affected docs are updated** and the **issue status is set and closed with the commit ref** — is met or carries a documented, justified deviation (rule 8). A findings-producing review (Tier 3, audits/campaigns) writes a report — prompt, verdict, findings — to `.process-work/reviews/` (`verification-independence.md`); with the `github-issues` module the report is published as an issue and follow-up findings become tracked work.{% if modules.telemetry %} Record the per-criterion verdicts as `GRADE` lines with `source=review` in the journal (`docs/process/modules/telemetry.md`).{% endif %}

## Quick

The Tier 0–1 shortcut: no separate plan file. Enters: a small, isolated request. Produces: the change plus a test (Tier 1). State goal, touched files, and risk before editing. Before finishing, take a light pass over the two checklist questions most likely to bite a small change: untrusted input reaching a sink, and duplicating an existing behavior instead of changing its owner. Escalate to Plan the moment persistence, auth, contracts, external integrations, or anything another component depends on come into scope.

## Spike

The named path for open-ended work — "can this be done?", "which library?",
"what does the API actually return?" — where the outcome is unknown, so
Brainstorm → Plan → Execute (which presumes you know what done looks like)
does not fit and forcing it produces invented acceptance criteria. Enters: a
question and an explicit **timebox**. Produces: **knowledge, never product
code** — a journal entry or design doc with the answer, and a decision record
when the answer settles something hard to reverse (mandatory rule 4). Spike
code is throwaway by declaration: it does not merge to the main branch, and a
feature built on what the spike learned re-enters through the normal cycle
(plan, tests, review) rather than promoting the prototype. Stopping at the
timebox with a partial answer is a successful spike — the timebox is the
scope. The spike itself is not tier-routed work; the follow-up change is.

## Debug

The root-cause entry point (mandatory rule 6). Enters: a bug, test failure, or unexpected behavior. Produces: a root-cause analysis before any fix. After two failed attempts at a symptom, stop patching and investigate why it happens; fix the cause, not the symptom.
{% if modules.github_issues %}
## Parallel agents

Several agents may work the backlog at once; the failure mode to design out is a *shared working tree* — two agents in one directory racing on the same `.git` HEAD/index. **Isolate:** give each agent its own `git worktree` or clone, never two in one directory; prefer server-side git (`gh pr merge --rebase`) over local `checkout`/`stash` that move HEAD out from under another agent. **Stay aware:** read live claims and in-flight work with `scripts/process/who_is_working.py` before starting, then claim (a comment naming agent/branch/scope, the `status:in-progress` label, and a heartbeat — see the claim workflow in the github-issues module) and never pick up already-claimed work. **Minimize conflict:** {% if modules.feature_registry %}take non-overlapping ready work (`scripts/process/story_order.py` prints the ready-to-start order), {% endif %}keep branches small and rebased, stage explicit paths (never `git add -A`), and serialize edits to high-contention artifacts. See where a human should look and steer in one view with `scripts/process/attention.py`. Two efforts on one behaviour declare *phase-of*/*supersede* rather than run in parallel (mandatory rule 4).
{% endif %}
